  "prompt": "Why can't a duck quack echo?",
  "response": "The idea that a duck's quack doesn't echo is actually a myth. Ducks do produce echoes when they quack, just like any other sound. The myth likely originated because a duck's quack is a relatively soft and short sound, and the echo may be difficult to hear, especially in open environments where sound tends to dissipate quickly.\n\nIn controlled environments or areas with reflective surfaces, a duck's quack can indeed produce an echo. The persistence of this myth may be due to the fact that people rarely experience conditions where the echo of a duck's quack is noticeable, leading to the misconception that it doesn't happen at all.",
